data.body:
- VSCode Version: 1.8.1
- OS Version: Windows 10 Home

The 'editor.action.addSelectionToNextFindMatch' command (_ctrl+d_) could have a case-sensitive variant, or a preference to make it case-sensitive.

The reason: I sometimes use it for a quick, localized find-and-replace, by selecting a piece of text, pressing _ctrl+d_ a few times, and then typing the replacement text.  However if it adds selections that differ in case, then I cannot type a replacement that matches the various cases.  For instance, if `[ ... ]` represents the selection here:

```javascript
const [table] = new Table();
// Tables have sizes:
const tableSize = table.size();
```

And I'd like to quickly change the three lowercase "table"s to "newTable", without changing the two capitalized "Table"s.  There isn't much value to me in selecting the capitalized ones, because the replacement I type will end up being the wrong case for one or the other.  So I'd like to quickly reach the following selection:

```javascript
 const [table] = new Table();
 // Tables have sizes:
 const [table]Size = [table].size();
```

Existing alternatives: The 'editor.action.moveSelectionToNextFindMatch' (_ctrl+k ctrl+d_) can be used to skip the unwanted regions, though that requires more keystrokes.  The following also works: "editor.action.startFindReplaceAction" (_ctrl+h_) - "toggleFindCaseSensitive" (_alt+c_)- type replacement - and _ENTER_ a few times, though that approach doesn't leave multiple cursors in place.
